INSERT INTO `meeting_notes` VALUES (2,'cmo-anindita-daily-standup','2026-03-09','cscs',3,'2026-03-09 11:15:20','2026-03-09 11:15:20'),(3,'marketing-standup-daily','2026-03-09','sjdhsds',3,'2026-03-09 11:15:28','2026-03-09 11:30:23'),(4,'marketing-standup-daily-tue','2026-03-09','Summary\n\n* Ad Campaign Performance Metrics\n    * @Anirudh reported daily ad spend of approximately ₹1.8 lakhs across different languages.[6:57]\n    * Total revenue from yesterday was ₹6.59 lakhs, with 492 total paid users.[7:46], [9:18]\n    * Cost per purchase varies by language: Kannada lowest at ₹205, Malayalam at ₹243, Tamil at ₹238, Telugu at ₹220.[5:06], [5:33], [5:28]\n    * CPC (Cost per Click) ranges between ₹45-₹50, with specific variations across different language campaigns.[2:35]\n* Language-Specific Ad Performance\n    * Language-wise ad spend: Tamil Nadu ₹1.81 lakhs, Karnataka ₹92,000, Kerala ₹72,000, Telangana/Andhra ₹116,000.[6:13], [6:20], [6:28], [6:34]\n    * @Anirudh noted that Kannada region has the lowest cost per purchase due to specific campaign characteristics.[5:48]\n* Campaign Optimization Strategy\n    * @Nandha suggested maintaining an average of 3 rows for each language campaign to ensure consistent performance.[7:57]\n    * Discussions around creating new campaigns and updating existing creatives to improve performance.[12:06]\n\n:white_check_mark: Action items\n\n* @Anirudh to calculate language-wise Return on Ad Spend (ROAs) and share detailed metrics.[12:23]\n* @Anirudh to create a separate campaign with existing creatives for testing.[11:47]\n* @Nandha to retrieve Lifetime Value (LTV) data from March/April for further analysis.[15:27]\n* @Anirudh to identify and document best and worst performing creatives across different language campaigns.[16:11]\n* Update daily revenue tracking sheet with comprehensive details to help team understand campaign performance.[12:39]',3,'2026-03-10 06:29:37','2026-03-10 06:29:37'),(5,'ops-standup-daily-tue','2026-03-09','Yesterday\'s work update: \nTamil: \nOnboarding: 156\nTickets: 116\nMail Queries: 40\n\nTelugu:\nTickets: 70\nOnboarding: 170\nWhatsapp Queries: 25\n\nMalayalam: \nTickets: 31\nOnboarding: 38\nWhatsapp queries: 15\nCalls: 8\n\nToday\'s more concentration should be: \nOnboarding: 50\nTickets has to be resolved within 1 hr.\nGet 10 reviews each.\n\nThe most frequent issues yesterday:\n1. Call amount not added accurately\n2. Creators are not picking the call\n3. 10 seconds creators speak, they cut the call\n4. Users amount getting deducted in 10 seconds\n5. user is busy\n6. Dual deduction of coins for users\n7. showing paid in the app but not credited the amount \n8. fake ids\n9. We need to stop making the tickets multiple times by the creator before resolving one.\n\nAlso, Ai tickets is not been resolved by ai, straightly redirected to the support team.',5,'2026-03-10 06:40:57','2026-03-10 06:41:40'),(6,'cmo-anindita-daily-standup-tue','2026-03-09','Summary\n\n* Lifetime Value (LTV) Calculation\n    * @anindita explained LTV calculation involves determining Average Revenue Per Paying User (ARPPU) and churn rate [2:43].\n    * For the last month, Malayalam market showed the highest ARPPU at ₹3,123 [2:17].\n    * Churn rate will be calculated by tracking how many unique users return after initial purchase [3:13].\n* Gifting Feature Potential\n    * @anindita identified gifting as a potential additional revenue stream beyond standard recharges [21:40].\n    * The platform can potentially keep a percentage of gift value while giving creators a portion [22:13].\n    * Currently, there\'s no tracking mechanism for gifting performance [17:02].\n* Social Media Content Strategy\n    * @anindita proposed multiple content categories including topical content, branding, customer testimonials, and trend-based posts [1:07:08].\n    * Creators are unlikely to be comfortable having their photos posted on the platform\'s social media [1:09:21].\n    * Recommended using tools like Asana or Zoho Social for content management [1:10:53].\n* Creator Engagement\n    * @anindita suggested motivating creators through recognition and potential bonus structures [12:35].\n    * Creators have an option to mark themselves as available during specific hours [9:27].\n    * The platform needs to analyze creator availability and engagement patterns [9:16].\n\n:white_check_mark: Action items\n\n* @Nandha to request developers add retention data tracking with daily, weekly, and monthly filter options [4:52].\n* @Nandha to implement gift tracking mechanism to understand revenue potential [22:41].\n* @Nandha to work with social media team to develop a content calendar with diverse post types [1:05:15].\n* Analyze creator availability hours and engagement patterns to optimize platform performance [9:16].\n* Develop a system to recognize and motivate top-performing creators [18:53].',3,'2026-03-10 09:54:27','2026-03-10 09:54:27'),(7,'cmo-creative-team-daily-standup-tue','2026-03-09','* Video Content Production\n    * @Nandha discussed creating 3 unique videos with the team, focusing on content generation and strategy. [3:20]\n    * @Krishnan Krishnan confirmed that scripts are ready and mentioned potential translation requirements for the videos. [3:26]\n    * The team discussed creating content for various platforms, including potential dating app and entertainment-oriented content. [8:14]\n* Social Media Strategy\n    * @Nandha indicated that social media posts are ready and being prepared for distribution. [7:28]\n    * @Krishnan Krishnan suggested using celebrity references and developing engaging content strategies. [10:46]\n    * The team planned to create content with meme references and trending approaches. [11:01]\n\n:white_check_mark: Action items\n\n* @Krishnan Krishnan to complete script translations and prepare content for different language markets. [3:46]\n* @anas to handle video generation and ensure technical aspects are managed. [9:54]\n* @Nandha to oversee video creation and social media team coordination. [10:10]\n* Develop content with a focus on entertainment and trending references. [11:01]',3,'2026-03-10 10:22:06','2026-03-10 10:22:06'),(8,'cfo-stand-up-meeting-tue','2026-03-09','Slack AI took notes for this huddle from 16:32:41 - 16:48:16 GMT+5:30. Ayush Agarwal and Shoyab conducted a detailed finance meeting discussing ongoing monthly financial tasks, GST filing, and service classification, with a focus on precise record-keeping and expense tracking. View huddle in channel\n\n:handshake: Attendees\n\n@Ayush Agarwal and @Shoyab\n\n:star: Summary\n\n* Monthly Financial Tasks\n    * @Ayush Agarwal reviewed ongoing financial tasks for February and March, including GST filing (GSTR 3V1, GSTR1), asset register balance, and bank statements. [1:46]\n    * @Shoyab confirmed work on multiple platforms and applications for financial record preparation. [2:37]\n    * Purchase records for February and March remain pending due to data is not updated in gov portal gstr2b. [3:31]\n* HSN Code Classification\n    * @Shoyab raised concerns about the current HSN code classification, suggesting modifications to ensure accurate service representation. [7:01]\n    * Detailed discussion about specific service codes, including 998439 for digital content services and potential alternatives. [8:05]\n    * Decision to confirm the final classification with Chaitra to ensure accuracy. [10:03]\n* Expense and Revenue Tracking\n    * @Shoyab emphasized the importance of tracking every expense to understand spending patterns and identify potential revenue leakages. [12:11]\n    * The team aims to implement a comprehensive tracking system that allows monthly expense control and potential savings. [12:04]\n\n:white_check_mark: Action items\n\n* @Shoyab to complete asset register balance by 12-3-2026, collaborating with @Ayush Agarwal. [11:01]\n* Reconcile tally data and review digital translation for window management. [11:23]\n* Confirm HSN code classification with Chatra to ensure accurate service representation. [10:03]\n* Review and complete March bank statements and purchase records. [3:31]',4,'2026-03-10 11:23:44','2026-03-10 11:23:44'),(9,'ops-standup-daily-wed','2026-03-09','* Ticket Resolution and AI Performance\n    * @Sneha Sunoj identified that AI is not consistently responding to initial tickets across all language channels.\n    * Some tickets are being resolved by AI, while others require manual intervention, creating inconsistent user support experiences.\n    * Total ticket volumes varied: Tamil (128), Telugu (120), Malayalam (47), with team members manually resolving most initial interactions.\n* User Experience and Complaints\n    * @Reshma Reshma reported users complaining about losing coins due to creators not appearing on camera, with multiple reports of fake IDs.\n    * Common user complaints include account deletion requests and issues with creator interactions.\n    * Recharge page issues and repeated queries were also noted by support team members.\n* Review Collection and Verification\n    * Review collection is low, with most team members collecting only 1-3 reviews per day.\n    * Some users are reluctant to provide reviews, requesting calls first.\n    * Pending creator verifications remain an issue, particularly for May 4th.\n\nAction items\n\n* @Sneha Sunoj requested investigation into AI ticket resolution inconsistencies across language channels.\n* @Sneha Sunoj instructed team to increase review collection, targeting 2-10 reviews per language team.\n* @Reshma Reshma to follow up on pending May 4th creator verifications and contact unresponsive creators.\n* @Sneha Sunoj will follow up on adding a reason box for user blocking in the admin panel.\n* Team to collect and report screenshots of specific user complaints and technical issues.',5,'2026-03-11 06:21:36','2026-03-11 06:21:36'),(10,'marketing-standup-daily-wed','2026-03-09','Summary\n\n* Language Performance Analysis\n    * @Anirudh provided detailed performance metrics across Tamil, Malayalam, Telugu, and Kannada languages [1:07].\n    * Malayalam showed the highest ROAS at 5.11 with GST and 6.03 without GST, indicating strong campaign performance [3:52].\n    * Telugu and Kannada showed lower ROAS compared to Malayalam, suggesting potential optimization opportunities [8:16][8:26].\n* Ad Spend and Registration\n    * Total ad spend varied significantly across languages, with Malayalam at 78,000 and Google/Facebook spending inconsistently [2:44].\n    * Registration numbers ranged from 397 in Malayalam to 911 in Tamil, highlighting variability in campaign effectiveness [4:44][4:56].\n* Creative Strategy\n    * @Anirudh identified MAA 009 and MAA 0013 as best-performing creatives [11:42].\n    * Podcast and conversation creatives showed varying performance across languages [12:42].\n    * Telugu podcast campaigns were noted to have high costs [13:11].\n\n:white_check_mark: Action items\n\n* @Anirudh to resolve Facebook ad spending issue and prepare to take campaigns live [9:00].\n* @Nandha to focus on improving creatives, particularly for underperforming languages [8:42].\n* Increase daily Google ad budget from 500 to 1000 to improve campaign reach [13:40].\n* Conduct a detailed review of creative performance across different language segments [10:25].',3,'2026-03-11 06:46:11','2026-03-11 06:46:11'),(11,'cmo-creative-team-daily-standup-wed','2026-03-09','Summary\n\n* Multilingual Content Strategy\n    * @Nandha discussed creating content in multiple languages including Tamil, Telugu, Malayalam, and Bengali [9:56]\n    * The team is exploring different video formats such as podcast, conversation videos, and audio/video calls [9:39]\n    * @Krishnan Krishnan emphasized developing creative assets for different language markets [7:36]\n* Video Production Status\n    * @anas reported completing 4 videos, including content about dogs, cats, green screen, and Bengal-related material [7:09]\n    * The team is considering various creative approaches, including potential \"double meaning\" content strategies [10:52]\n\n:white_check_mark: Action items\n\n* @Nandha to coordinate next set of creative assets for multiple language markets [7:19]\n* @anas to continue video production, focusing on diverse content types [7:00]\n* Team to review and expand multilingual content strategy across different video formats [9:39]',3,'2026-03-11 07:04:04','2026-03-11 07:04:04'),(12,'cmo-anindita-daily-standup-wed','2026-03-09','Summary\n\n* Kannada Language Performance Strategy\n    * @Nandha wants to increase revenue and user base in the Kannada language segment [10:01].\n    * @anindita suggested exploring discount strategies and refreshing creative content to improve user engagement [4:38].\n    * Currently, first-time users receive 50 free coins, which translates to 4-5 minutes of audio call time [5:53].\n* Creator Onboarding and User Ratio\n    * @anindita proposed calculating an optimal creator-to-user ratio, suggesting approximately 25 female creators per 100 male users [15:53].\n    * According to internal insights, each language should have 70-80 creators to support a large user base [16:19].\n    * @Nandha wants detailed data on creator numbers and performance for each language [17:04].\n* Creative Content Strategy\n    * @anindita recommended refreshing creatives weekly for user-targeted content to maintain engagement [7:16].\n    * Creatives for user-targeted campaigns should change weekly, while creator-targeted creatives can be used for 2-3 weeks [11:27].\n    * Current creatives are approximately one month old and may need replacement [7:05].\n* Call Engagement Focus\n    * Video calls generate more revenue compared to audio calls [6:04].\n    * @Nandha confirmed creators are generally comfortable with video calls [19:05].\n    * @anindita plans to develop strategies to push more video call engagement [19:17].\n\n:white_check_mark: Action items\n\n* @anindita to consult with Sneha about precise creator numbers for each language [26:40].\n* @anindita to develop strategies to increase video call engagement in Kannada language [8:22].\n* @anindita to analyze historical performance data (September to March) to understand user trends [20:20].\n* @Nandha to provide language-wise performance reports for detailed analysis [15:53].\n* Team to refresh creative content weekly for user-targeted campaigns [7:16].',3,'2026-03-11 07:43:29','2026-03-11 07:43:29'),(13,'cmo-social-media-team-daily-standup-wed','2026-03-09','Summary\n\n* Poster Design Concept\n    * @tiyasa is creating posters featuring AI-generated images of young professionals [1:14].\n    * Poster design includes visual elements like chat bubbles and light bulbs to represent collaboration [1:24].\n    * The headline will emphasize \"Connect, Collaborate and Create\" for Bangalore Connect [1:24].\n* Video Content Performance\n    * @Nandha and @tiyasa acknowledged low view counts for current videos [3:25].\n    * @tiyasa observed that AI-generated videos are not performing as well as organic content [5:03].\n    * Proposed strategy to increase visibility includes having company employees share videos on Instagram stories [4:03].\n* Content Collaboration Strategy\n    * @tiyasa will prepare daily content and send to @Nandha before 6 PM for posting [3:00].\n    * Both parties agreed to mutually share and support content creation efforts [4:48].\n\n:white_check_mark: Action items\n\n* @tiyasa to complete poster design with AI-generated professional images [1:14].\n* @Nandha to post content sent by @tiyasa daily before specified time [3:00].\n* Explore options for increasing video view counts, including employee content sharing [4:03].\n* Continue experimenting with different video content types to improve performance [5:03].',3,'2026-03-11 09:50:30','2026-03-11 09:50:30'),(14,'cfo-stand-up-meeting-wed','2026-03-09','Slack AI took notes for this huddle from 15:12:13 - 15:20:31 GMT+5:30. Ayush Agarwal and Shoyab conducted a detailed financial review meeting focusing on GST filing, revenue calculations, and pending administrative tasks for their organization. View huddle in channel\n\n:handshake: Attendees\n\n@Shoyab and @Ayush Agarwal\n\n:star: Summary\n\n* GST Filing and Revenue Calculations\n    * @Ayush Agarwal discussed the need to correctly fill JSTR1 app SAC code and calculate revenue for all apps [1:25].\n    * There was a discussion about how to handle pre-GST registration sales turnover, with two potential approaches: adding it to the February month or segregating it month-wise [4:52].\n    * @Ayush Agarwal suggested filing the previous month\'s GST in March and addressing an additional ₹20 lakh payment [5:25].\n* SAC Code Confirmation\n    * @Shoyab explained that different Ola services might require different SAC codes, depending on service assumptions [6:36].\n    * There was uncertainty about the correct SAC code application across multiple apps [6:29].\n* Work Schedule and Next Steps\n    * @Ayush Agarwal outlined a plan to complete tasks by 4:30 PM, including calling Prame for SAC code confirmation [7:35].\n    * The team planned to prepare for an upcoming meeting with the CFO and CA [7:35].\n\n:white_check_mark: Action items\n\n* @Shoyab to call Prame and confirm SAC codes by 4:30 PM [7:22].\n* @Shoyab to finalize GST filing calculations and prepare documentation [8:44].\n* @Ayush Agarwal to prepare for meeting with CFO and CA after 4:30 PM [7:35].\n* Send Form 16 to all companies [4:11].\n* Prepare TDS certificates and asset register documents [7:35].',4,'2026-03-11 09:57:16','2026-03-11 09:57:16'),(15,'tech-lead-hima-standup-thu','2026-03-09','Summary\n\n* Sprint and Project Status\n    * @Rishabh Kumar has been primarily working on Ludo and resolving UI issues\n    * The UI sprint is nearly complete, with only one minor bug pending related to button icon overlapping\n    * @Yuvanesh suggested focusing on finishing Ludo this week and addressing sudden dashboard changes in the upcoming sprint\n* Technical Issues\n    * Video call functionality reported some inconsistencies, including face detection and camera preview problems\n    * @Rishabh Kumar confirmed that after extensive testing, the video call feature is working correctly\n    * @Raksha Agarwal experienced difficulties with updating and screen recording, potentially due to connectivity issues.',34,'2026-03-12 05:22:42','2026-03-12 05:22:42'),(16,'ops-standup-daily-thu','2026-03-09','* Performance Metrics\n    * @Sneha Sunoj reviewed creator registration and verification data from March 10th, noting Telugu region had the highest backlog with 7 pending creators out of 64 registered.[4:16]\n    * Marathi and Kannada regions demonstrated the best same-day verification rates.[4:37]\n* Call Connection Issues\n* Warning System\n* Individual Development\n\n:white_check_mark: Action items\n\n* @Sneha Sunoj wants team to concentrate on improving review ratings.[11:35]\n* @Deeksha and @Ranjini to change notifications today.[11:45]\n* Investigate and resolve ongoing ticket with repeated queries.[12:04]\n* Follow up on recharge page screenshot issue and ensure ticket resolution.',5,'2026-03-12 06:18:33','2026-03-12 06:18:33'),(17,'marketing-standup-daily-thu','2026-03-09','Summary\n\n* Facebook Ad Verification Challenge\n    * @Anirudh is experiencing issues with Facebook ad verification due to video content mentioning \"make money\" themes, which is causing ads to be flagged.: [0:55]\n    * The team is exploring potential certification solutions to resolve the FSV (likely Facebook Specific Verification) problem.: [1:13]\n* Campaign Performance Metrics\n    * Cost per purchase varies significantly across languages, with Tamil having the highest at 297 and Malayalam the lowest at 4.57.: [5:15]\n    * Registration data shows variations in male and female user acquisition across different language segments.: [11:57]\n    * Language-specific performance metrics were carefully reviewed, including spend rates and registration numbers.: [8:31]\n* Campaign Strategy\n    * @Anirudh made minor budget adjustments for lookalike audiences, reducing budget in one ad group and increasing in another.: [2:08]\n    * The team discussed launching new creatives and optimizing campaigns across multiple languages.: [15:20]\n\n:white_check_mark: Action items\n\n* @Anirudh to pursue Facebook certification to resolve ad verification issues.: [1:13]\n* @Anirudh to launch all new creatives for the campaign.: [15:20]\n* @Nandha to guide creation of Bengali campaign with specific text guidelines, including primary text about \"talking to girls\".: [17:52]\n* Review and potentially adjust budget allocations across language-specific campaigns based on current performance metrics.: [2:08]',3,'2026-03-12 06:33:08','2026-03-12 06:33:08'),(18,'full-stack-dev-astro-standup-thu','2026-03-09','Summary\n\n* Project Status and Technical Issues\n    * @Barkha Agarwal reported completing most project components, but noted that avtar remains unfinished [1:10].\n    * There were persistent audio communication challenges during the meeting, with @Rishabh Kumar repeatedly asking @Barkha Agarwal to clarify her statements T7519[1:20].\n    * An API key issue was identified, with @Barkha Agarwal mentioning the key worked yesterday but is currently non-functional [3:49].\n* Website and Integration Status\n    * @Barkha Agarwal confirmed the website has been prepared and is ready to be made live [2:01].\n    * @Rishabh Kumar plans to personally verify the website once it is deployed [2:14].\n    * Avatar integration remains an outstanding technical challenge that needs resolution [4:11].',35,'2026-03-12 06:37:30','2026-03-12 06:37:30'),(19,'product_manager-daily-standup-dhanush-thu','2026-03-09','1.We will discuss the 2nd version app conversion and product growth implementation on Wednesday next week.(March 18)\n\n\n2.The Business 